 the ordinary people whose lives were never recorded in history books. Focusing primarily on these unknown citizens-an accountant in the first Treasury Department, a coachmaker whose clients were politicians doing business at the State House, an African American founder of St. Thomas's African Episcopal Church, and others-Yamin presents a colorful portrait of old Philadelphia. She also discusses political aspects of archaeology today-who supports particular projects and why, and what has been lost to bulldozers and heedlessness. Digging in the City of Brotherly Love tells the exhilarating story of doing archaeology in the real world and using its findings to understand the past.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aArchaeologistsxPennsylvaniaxPhiladelphia. 0aArchaeologistszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aArchaeology and historyxPennsylvaniaxPhiladelphia. 0aArchaeology and historyzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)xPennsylvaniaxPhiladelphia. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aHistoric sitesxPennsylvaniaxPhiladelphia. 0aHistoric siteszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 0aUrban archaeologyxPennsylvaniaxPhiladelphia. 0aUrban archaeologyzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300142648423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300142648.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles